      <solution id="idp3199696">
        <title>37. Hepatic portal venous gas</title>
        <para id="id2254038">The radiographic hallmark of this condition is a 
spidery pattern of tubular radiolucencies branching toward the liver edge (image 
below). Gas in the biliary tract is located more centrally and may appear in the 
gallbladder and extrahepatic biliary ducts as well. </para>
        <para id="id2254048">
          <media id="idm2035600" alt=""><image src="../../media/Case_37-diag1-1.jpg" mime-type="image/jpeg"/></media>
        </para>
        <para id="id2254081">Hepatic portal venous gas usually indicates 
necrotic bowel in adults and necrotizing enterocolitis in infants. Emergency 
celiotomy in this patient demonstrated gangrene of the jejunum and gas in the 
portal vein. Blood cultures grew <emphasis>Klebsiella</emphasis> and 
<emphasis>Enterococcus</emphasis> species. The patient died 10 days after 
surgery.</para>
      </solution>
